Duris edit
Duris edit - Last Edited: 2008-08-22 20:24:07 by Jexni
======================================================
Duris Edit (Formerly Diku Edit) is a program used to create new zones for the
game. See below for off-site link to download the most recent version
(hopefully... DE is a project of someone not affiliated with Duris per se).
Getting Started:
Step One - Save your copy of Duris Edit into a new folder.
It's advisable to keep each zone's files in separate folders within your DE
folder, but keep in mind that DE will need to be copied into each folder to
edit your new zone.  For the purpose of this tutorial, I'll say my zone's
name is "uberzone".
Step Two - Open DE.exe.  DE will ask you if you are creating a new zone, or
working upon an already existing zone.  For a new zone, type 'N'.  Next you
will specify the name of the zone (and all associated files).
Step Three - After step two you should now have the Duris Edit window open
and you are free to create.  A listing of commands is available by typing
"command".  The help is somewhat limited, but includes enough information to
get by in most instances.
Editing a new zone:
Specify a starting vnum for rooms, objs, and mobs: For now, just go with 1
as your starting vnum (this number can be changed easily w/ the renumber
command when you are given a block of vnums from the staff).
Enter a new name for the zone: Kind of self explanatory here.  Ansi is
encouraged, but please be tasteful.
Zone's zone number is equal to 0 - specify a valid zone number: just go with
1(again this will be set by the staff upon submission).
And here you are in DE ready to write your zone.
----
Some Things to Keep in Mind:
Mapping your zone out on graph paper before beginning will help you to keep
track of your rooms, and also give you a better focus on what the theme of
your zone is(a well laid out zone is going to be more cohesive and make more
sense than one that runs all over and has rooms leading every which way).
Room descriptions should always start with a 3 space indent on the first line
and should be at least 4 lines in length. The length of each line should
generally go to about the 80th column without counting ansi codes.
   This is a formatted line of the correct length including several ansi codes.
Room Names should be capitalized the same way as titles:
The Dreaded and Much Feared Room of Ownage
Ansi is an art form! Read "help ansi" on the mud for more information on this.
Try not to create an eyesore as it will annoy the staff and generally degrade
the quality of the zone.
Most of all enjoy yourself. Writing a zone can take a long time, but if you're
having fun it's worth it.
==See also==
zones, credits, website, ansi
