New Player Guides
New Player Guides - Last Edited: 2007-04-22 22:12:53 by Unknown
===============================================================
Welcome to Duris, Land of Bloodlust! This guide is intended to get new players out
and about with a decent idea of how to use their character. This guide is also not
done, your feedback and ideas are always appreciated in the Duris Forums.
http://duris.game-host.org/viewtopic.php?t=1314
==Settings==
Duris is a very detailed world but sometimes it's just too much, "tog brief" will remove
the room descriptions. These can still be seen by "look room" or "l room" for short.
Typing "display" alone will show a list of options while "display all" will set your
prompt to twoline and in battle will display the tank and enemy and their conditions.
While it is against the training of a Paladin to automatically finish off their victims, for
all others typing "tog vicious" will cause you to strike your opponent as they lay
incapacitated at your feet. This setting will affect to any pets you have or any guards
that might be assisting you.
==Social Interaction==
NChat is a channel reserved for lowbies and Newbie Guides. Typing "nchat" and then
your message will make you heard. Once grouped, to communicate with all those in
your group you can gsay. Typing "gsay" and then your message will make you heard.
Tell is a private way to talk to anyone conscious and visible to you on your side of the
racewar. Typing "tell <playername>" and then your message will make you heard.
==Spells 101==
Typing "spell" will show you your spell list. The lighter spells are available for you to
learn from your guild teacher. Priests do not need to scribe spells. You may scribe
any of your spells into your spellbook from another player's book though if you haven't
attained the spell circle you can't cast them. If you are learning from a teacher you
"hold book" and "hold quill" have a seat and "prac <spellname>". If you're copying
spells into your spellbook from another player grab your book and quill and then
"scribe <spellname>". For casters, each level you gain will award you one spell slot,
some levels more than one. Next memorize or pray the spells you want to cast
"mem/pray <spell name>", and then "meditate
", meditating gives you a chance to
complete your study in half the time. Spells ready, "cast '<spellname>' <target>" or
just cast '<spellname>' for self only spells or to target the engaged.
==Skills 101==
Typing "skills" will show you the skill list. Skills raise automatically until lvl 30 at
which point they will all be at a minimum of 40. Skills attained after level 30 will begin
at 40 as well. Skills may be practiced ad naseum to notch or may be bought for a
hefty price at your teacher. Ye feel yer skill in explaining improving!
==Equipment 101==
Determining the best equipment to wear is not always easy. Everyone benefits from
gear that improves their hitpoints, stats, saving throws, and armor class; however,
different classes have different priorities. A Cleric with 90 wisdom is going to want to
find some +wis eq to reach their prime praying time; whereas, a Sorcerer with 100 int
will search far and wide for something that is max_int, thus increasing his intelligence
over 100 and lowering his memtime further. While Mages and Priests search for hp
gear to raise they low health, Fighters and Rogues are searching for weapons and
armor to raise their battle prowess, items that affect their hitroll and damroll or stats
that are not quite 100.
When purchasing items in a shop it is not possible to determine their stats. Once the
item is in your grasp there are various ways to determine it's potential. Specialized
Bards called Minstrels are able to examine a piece of equipment and determine its
bonuses much like the 5th circle Conjurer spell identify. Alchemists, and all other
Bards, can lore an item to determine the the general stats. At the bank your locker
can be accessed for a small fee relative to how many items you have stored. Once
inside you may also "stat <item>" for 1 plat to see general stats. The auction house
will reveal an items advantages or disadvantages, "auction info <item number>".
There are also ID scrolls for sale (usually for around 4 plat). You may "recite scroll
<item>" to glean the information, though the item must be in your inventory. At times
it might just be easiest to check your attributes, switch equipment, save, and check
your attributes again to determine the best piece of equipment to wear.
==Battle Time==
A wise man knows his opponent before striking. To determine the difference in levels
between you and the mob you can consider killing it by typing "con <victim>". This is
only a level vs level evaluation and does not account for class differences.
==Experience==
Congratulations! You've slaughtered your first stray cat. If done correctly a message
of "You have received your share of experience." should have shown after the kill. This
message will differ later if you keep killing the same mob (see trophy). To check your
progress type "experience" or "exp", see also Exp guide for some tips. New skills and/or spells will become available to
you as you progress in level by killing mobs or completing quests. Certain levels will
award more than just an increase in your hitpoints. At level 20 you will be able to see
the numbers for your stats in "attributes" or "attr". Though some clans may choose
not to make you a member at level 25, you are eligible to become a member of a
player guild or form your own. At level 30 you may choose to specialize your class.
Typing "spec" at anytime will show you the available options.
==World Quests==
World Quests are a recent addition to Duris. The bartenders of Bloodmoon Tavern in
southeastern Tharnadia and Karuna Bar in the upper east district of Woodseer will
sell these quests to any adventurer. For a small fee they will even help you locate the
zone. These quests can then be shared with a small group by the one who purchased
them. The rewards for completing a go kill such'n'such number of so'n'so mobs is a
piece of equipment from that zone at random and experience.
