Ship cargo
Ship cargo - Last Edited: 2013-04-24 18:11:34 by targ
=====================================================
Ship Cargo
=========================================
Sailing cargo is the best way to make money on Duris, but it requires
significant investments. First, you need to buy a cargo ship. Amount
of cargo your ship can carry is shown on hulls list. Bigger ships can
carry a lot of cargo, but they are slow, especially when fully loaded.
The good way to start cargoing is to use smaller cargo ships, they dont
carry much, but move faster and you dont risk as much if something goes
_wrong_.
Each cargo crate weight 2 units, thus fully loaded ships will go MUCH
slower than its max speed. This makes you vulnerable to pirates and other
players attack. Of course, you can jettison you cargo and make a run for it,
but it doesnt always work and cargo worth money. So its good idea to equip
your ship with at least some weapons to be able to fight back.
To buy cargo, go to one of the major docks in the world, and dock your
ship there. Then type "list cargo". This gives you a list of the one type
of cargo you can BUY at this dock, and the many other types of cargo you
can SELL here. It also gives you a list of prices, which are vital to
actually MAKING MONEY, which is the sole purpose of running cargo. Make
sure you buy low and sell high. Stand on the dock you've chosen, with your
ship present and type  "buy cargo #" where # is the number of cargo crates
you wish to buy.
Once you buy the cargo, you sail to a DIFFERENT major dock.  Disembark, and
type "sell cargo". You should type "list cargo" to ensure you"re making a
profit first.  Then, repeat, buy, sail somewhere, sell, get rich...
When someone sells cargo at dock, its price there goes down. When someone
buys cargo, the price goes up. Watch out for other players running cargo
and ruining your profit. If you already bought some cargo, but changed your
plans, you can sell it back to local merchants (at lower price, of course).
The further is your destination dock from the place where certain cargo is
produced, the higher it will sell there. You have to choose between shorter
low-profit trips and longer but profitable ones.
Additionally, you may purchase a diplomat's flag for your ship which will discourage
pirates from attacking you but will incur a 10% tax on any cargo you sold.
Note: Each major docks has it's own type of cargo. Therefore, by number of
types of cargo available, you can determine how many major ports there are,
and even approximate what continent any specific type of cargo can be
purchased at.
Example: Elven Wines are bought on the Elven Continent.
Note: If you summon your ship to another location, all cargo in your ship
will be lost. Use summon only as a last resort if you run cargo.
Note: A sloop and a Yacht have very limited space. You can move some cargo
using these ships, but generally its a waste of time.
Note: If you are attacked during cargo run, and you would rather try to escape
than fight back, or you want to be at full speed to fight back you can
type "order jettison cargo" or "order jettison cargo <n crates>" and your
top speed will go up accordingly.
Note: When cargo is jettisoned (or when ship with cargo is sunk), some of it
stays afloat, and you can pick it up using "order salvage". You can see floating
cargo on map. Even warships, that normally dont carry cargo, can pick some
that way.
Note: Some port merchant sell and buy illegal goods, but they only deal with
well-known captains and experienced crews. If your manage to buy such goods,
hide it well on your ship, because they will be confiscated by authorities
if found. The more crates of cargo you have on your ship, the easier is to
hide crates with contraband.
