Ship Combat
Ship Combat - Last Edited: 2015-07-09 18:02:30 by lohrr
=======================================================
Ship Combat
=========================================
Combat on the ship system works on the principle of firing arcs,
single target, and damage points.
==Firing Arcs==
Firing arcs are the direction your weapons are pointing on your ship. For
example, a ballistae mounted on your Port(Left) side is pointing to the
ship"s left, so if the target is on the right side, it is out of that
particular weapon"s arc, so if weapons are mounted only on the forward arc,
that means the ship only has a limited arc of fire in the front. If a ship
has weapons on all four parts of the ship it can shoot in any direction.
==Target==
Fighting in ships requires you to lock onto another ship. This uses the
ID of the ship (covered in "help Ship_Looks"). The syntax is "Lock <ID>"
When you are locked onto a ship, your crew will try to attack that ship and
only that ship when you order them to fire weapons or ram. However, you can
reassign the Lock ID at any time, as often and as quickly as you wish.
==Damage==
When a ship is hit, it is hit on one of the four sides. Each side has
two types of HP, armor and hull. Armor is made to take damage, as long as
a ship has armor, its weapons and insides are protected unless enemy scores
a critical hit that penetrates the armor. Once the ship's armor is blasted away
however, damage goes to the hull of the ship. Hull is basically the framework
of the ship, hits in the hull can knock the crew to the ground or damage weapons.
Once all the hull of a side is gone, the ship is taking on water, not enough to
sink it, but enough to immobilize it. Once two hull sides are blown away,
the ship no longer can float and will sink. If the ship is fast enough and
doesn't want to get blown up, they have the choice of running, but be
warned, the rear of a ship has less armor and more delicate structure than
the rest of the ship (Like the Rudder) so the ship will be quite vulnerable there.
Also when a ship gets hit, it has a chance of getting hit in the sails which
makes the ship not able to move as fast (can"t move if your sails have big
holes in it), and even possibly, with enough hits, the sail can get completely
destroyed, making the ship immobile.
==Repairs==
Your crew will try their best to repair damage done to ship during combat, but
they only can do so much outside of dock. When ship is anchored and not engaged in
any actions, it gives crew better chance to do repairs. If ship is immobilized,
crew might patch it enough to start moving again, but they can do it only in
anchored state.
==Weapons aiming==
The chance to hit target ship is determined by the range to target, target's size
and by target's movement relatively to your ship. The catapult-type weapons mostly
affected by distance changing speed, the ballistas and beam-type weapons are mostly
affected by angle speed of the target. Basically, the best situation is when
target is close and moves in the same direction at the same speed as your ship.
==Ramming==
If you ran out of ammo or feel like going banzai, you can try ramming enemy ship.
Syntax is "order ram". This will switch your ship into ramming mode, in which it will
immediately ram the target as soon as it gets into your front arc at distance less
than one. While your crew prepares for ram, their actions are limited. They can still
maneuver the ship, aim and fire weapons, but they arent able to do long work like repairs
or weapon reloading. To stand down from ramming state, do "order ram off".
Your need to maintain some speed to do ramming. Upon ramming, both ships recieve
massive damage, but extent of that damage is affected by ships relative size and relative
movement during the ram. Ramming a clipper with cruiser has devastating effect, but
good luck catching it into ramming position. Ramming a cruiser with clipper is easy but
will cause much more damage to ramming ship that to target. If your ram the target from
behind, it will be weak due to low relative speed. If you ram target head-on, your ship
will recieve a lot of damage also.
The best is to ram ship of close size ortogonally into the side at full speed.
Note: Many players will disembark their own ship after they immobilize
yours or drop its speed below certain point, and then board yours to kill
you AND destroy your ship afterwards. You can also do this yourself
(just don't die on THEIR ship).
Note: After Sinking a ship, use the command "Get Money" to collect the prize
money for sinking your enemy. The prize (frags, epics, money) will be split among
the ships that took part in sinking.
Note: You can get in group with other captains, if both you and group leader are
on the bridge of their undocked ship.
Note: It takes about 75 sec to 2 1/2 minutes for a player's ship to finish sinking.
